f the user removes required fields (like setting nickname to empty string, or re
moving avatar_url). The DTO allows these fields to be optional in PATCH, but the
re\'s no logic to re-evaluate `is_complete` after an update. So a user could com
plete profile, then patch it to remove their avatar, and `is_complete` would sti
ll be `true`. This is a potential data integrity issue.\n\nHowever, looking at t
he DTOs, `nickname`, `gender`, `birth_date`, `latitude`, `longitude` are all opt
ional in `UpdateProfileDto`. The service just updates whatever is provided. It d
oesn\'t re-validate completeness. This means a user could set `avatar_url: null`
via PATCH and still have `is_complete = true`. The `ProfileCompletionGuard` woul
d let them through.\n\nThis is a business logic bug - `updateProfile` should re-
validate profile completeness and update `is_complete` accordingly.\n\nWait, act
ually the DTO validation doesn\'t prevent empty strings or nulls explicitly. `@I
sString()` allows empty string `""`. So a user could PATCH `{ "nickname": "" }` 
and the service would set nickname to empty string without affecting `is_complet
e`.\n\nThis is definitely an issue.\n\nAlso, `createProfile` manually validates 
required fields instead of relying on DTO validation. The `CreateProfileDto` mar
ks `nickname`, `gender`, `birth_date`, `latitude`, `longitude` as required (no `
@IsOptional()`), but `avatar_url` is optional in the DTO even though the service
requires it. So there\'s a mismatch between DTO and service validation.\n\nAnoth
er issue: The `CreateProfileDto` doesn\'t have `@IsNotEmpty()` on `nickname`, so
an empty string would pass DTO validation but fail the manual service check `!dt
